  "updated_summary": "Joshua Liendo, a swimmer with a beard, curly hair, and a gold chain, wearing a white Florida Gators t-shirt, speaks from an indoor swimming pool arena with a high arched ceiling and a red digital timer, reflecting on his connection to Trinidad, where he spent his childhood before moving to Canada at age 10, and expressing that he misses the weather, people, and lifestyle, calling it \"awesome\" and \"beautiful.\" Intercut is a bald Man in Glasses, in a grey suit, seated at a desk in a brightly lit studio with a laptop, who interviews Liendo about his Canadian identity and role model status, noting Liendo is the \"first Black swimmer\" to achieve certain feats and often the \"only Black swimmer\" in races, questioning the lack of diversity. Liendo advocates for pursuing passions, crediting his parents' sacrifices, and agrees that his success will inspire \"kids of all colors, but certainly Black kids,\" to consider swimming. The narrative transitions to high-energy live competition footage from the 'Men’s 100m Butterfly FINAL' at the Fukuoka 2023 World Aquatics Championships, with energetic sports commentary, dramatic music, and crowd cheering identifying \"Josh Liendo from Canada\" as a \"Commonwealth Games champion\" and \"bronze medalist.\" Swimmers, including Liendo, dive from starting blocks, with underwater cameras capturing powerful strokes and real-time race data, as the commentator highlights Liendo in \"second place\" and \"extending the lead\" amidst splashing sounds. Close-ups of Liendo in competition attire, wearing a black swim cap with 'CAN' and 'LIENDO' and colorful goggles, are interspersed, reinforcing on-screen text 'Joshua Liendo swims into the history books' and the CBCNEWS logo. Liendo also expresses admiration for Allen Iverson after watching a documentary, connecting with his authenticity and impact. The Man in Glasses shifts the conversation to the Canadian swim team, highlighting the women's success and asking Liendo if this is discussed among the men, to which Liendo confirms they always talk about the women's strong performance and the men's need to step up."
